h(H,1,2,3)(H,4,8)(H,5,6,7,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"H3N\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_023\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"cyanamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cyanamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2N2/c2-1-3/h(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_024\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3HN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethynyl cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cyanoacetylene\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3HN/c1-2-3-4/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_025\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H15N3O3P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"phosphoric diamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"diamidophosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, H2-rich, pH 9-11\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface catalytic hydrogenation of CO2 to reduced C1 species on Fe-S phases under alkaline vent conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Preiner et al. (2020) demonstrated CO2 fixation with H2 on greigite, magnetite, and related hydrothermal minerals at 100\u00b0C under alkaline conditions, giving substantial formate yields; this provides a hydrothermal entry point into reduced carbon chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reduction of CO2-derived carbon to formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"313-363K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni-doped mackinawite / magnetite-like hydrothermal mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent reactor analogue with proton gradient context\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrogen-driven reduction of CO2 at iron-sulfur mineral interfaces produces C1 oxygenates including formaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Herschy et al. (2014) detected formaldehyde from H2 + CO2 in alkaline vent simulation reactors using Ni-doped mackinawite catalysts. This justifies formaldehyde as a hydrothermal feedstock exported to surface settings.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal proto-energetic synthesis of acetyl phosphate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_020\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS2/Fe0 mineral redox system\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"speculative connecting step consistent with acetyl-phosphate-first vent scenarios\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduced C1/C2 carbon and phosphate are coupled at Fe-rich hydrothermal interfaces to generate an activated acyl phosphate donor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Lane and Martin's hydrothermal framework and the review identify acetyl phosphate as a plausible proto-ATP intermediate, but no single direct geochemical synthesis under the exact full sequence is established; this step is explicitly speculative yet necessary to connect vent carbon fixation to the experimentally validated ATP-forming step of Pinna et al. (2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface photoredox synthesis of glycolaldehyde from HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite analogs)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-driven Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanide photoredox network on mineral-bearing surface settings\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation in cyanosulfidic surface environment\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN undergoes UV-driven homologation/reduction in a catalytic photoredox network to produce C2 sugar precursors.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson & Sutherland (2012) demonstrated UV-driven formation of glycolaldehyde from HCN via Cu-cyanide photoredox chemistry, and Patel et al. (2015) integrated such sugar-fragment chemistry into a broader cyanosulfidic network. Surface mineral agents are included to satisfy the network schema, though the key experimental catalyst is the Cu cyanide photoredox system.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface photoredox synthesis of glyceraldehyde from HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite analogs)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        