ehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite\", \"magnetite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"313-363K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni-doped mackinawite with magnetite-like hydrothermal surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent reactor, proton/pH gradients possible\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Partial reduction of CO2 by H2 on sulfide surfaces generates formaldehyde as a reactive carbonyl feedstock.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Bench-top alkaline vent reactor experiments detected formaldehyde from H2 + CO2 with Ni-doped mackinawite under vent-like conditions; Herschy et al. (2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal acetyl phosphate generation from vent proto-metabolism\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite\", \"pyrite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"313-363K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"iron-sulfur mineral assemblage\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal setting; connection step is speculative but motivated by acetyl-phosphate-first protoenergetics\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduced C1 vent carbon chemistry is coupled conceptually to phosphate activation to supply acetyl phosphate as a proto-energetic donor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step is included as a necessary connector rather than a directly demonstrated single-reaction route. The review identifies acetyl phosphate as a plausible proto-ATP in hydrothermal scenarios and notes that integrating its formation geochemically remains unresolved; de Duve (1991, 1995), Lane and Martin as summarized in the review, and Pinna et al. (2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN photoredox synthesis of glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2\", \"molybdenite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photoredox mineral surface context\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation; literature uses Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanide photoredox, represented here in a mineral-rich photochemical surface setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photoredox homologation of cyanide-derived carbon produces C2 and C3 sugar fragments without requiring free ribose.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde formation from HCN under UV via copper photoredox was demonstrated by Ritson and Sutherland (2012) and integrated into cyanosulfidic networks by Patel et al. (2015). Mineral agents are included to satisfy network schema for surface settings, but the key literature support is the Cu photoredox chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomerization to DAMN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO2\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"278-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"requires concentrated HCN or concentration by freezing/evaporation; alkaline conditions favor oligomerization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential HCN oligomerization furnishes the tetramer diaminomaleonitrile as the key bottleneck intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"DAMN is the accepted critical intermediate in adenine synthesis from HCN; Sanchez, Ferris and Orgel (1967), Or\u00f3 (1961), Roy et al. (2007), and Sandstr\u00f6m et al. (2025). Mineral surfaces are used here as plausible concentrating substrates, while the core chemistry is literature-supported.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photoisomerization of DAMN to AICN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-active mineral surface context\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"strong UV irradiation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical rearrangement of DAMN furnishes 4-aminoimidazole-5-carbonitrile, a purine-ring precursor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Near-quantitative UV photoisomerization of DAMN to AICN is part of the accepted HCN-to-adenine route; Sanchez, Ferris and Orgel (1967), and discussed in the review with Sandstr\u00f6m et al. (2025).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"AICN plus HCN to adenine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO2\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"concentrating mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"ammonium cyanide-rich or evaporative settings; days-scale heating possible\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fifth cyanide equivalent closes the purine ring to give adenine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This follows the classic Or\u00f3 adenine synthesis framework via HCN pentamerization through DAMN/AICN; Or\u00f3 (1961), Sanchez et al. (1967), Roy et al. (2007), Sandstr\u00f6m et al. (2025).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide mineral-catalyzed adenine synthesis\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"433K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and/or montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"neat formamide heating\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Thermally activated formamide condensation on mineral surfaces yields purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including adenine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Heating neat formamide with TiO2 or montmorillonite produces nucleobases, including adenine; Saladino et al. (2003, 2004), with broader iron-sulfur/meteorite extensions in Saladino et al. (2008, 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanamide plus glycolaldehyde to 2-aminooxazole\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"borate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"concentrating evaporitic mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"neutral to mildly basic aqueous conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation of glycolaldehyde with cyanamide forms the heterocycle 2-aminooxazole.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the entry step of the Sutherland bypass route to nucleotide chemistry; Anastasi et al. (2006) and Powner et al. (2009).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"2-Aminooxazole plus glyceraldehyde to ribo-aminooxazoline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate-assisted sugar organization\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"reported 44% ribo-aminooxazoline with some arabino isomer\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"C2 and C3 sugar fragments combine through aminooxazole chemistry to give a pentose-derived heterocycle.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ribo-aminooxazoline formation from 2-aminooxazole and glyceraldehyde was demonstrated by Anastasi et al. (2006) and underpins the Powner et al. (2009) bypass strategy.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Borate-stabilized pentose formation to ribose\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals\", \"molybdenite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate and molybdate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline evaporitic pools; borate stabilization and molybdate-guided rearrangements\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde enter borate/molybdate-directed sugar chemistry yielding pentoses including ribose, while borate stabilizes the ribose furanose form.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ricardo et al. (2004) showed borate stabilization of ribose, Furukawa et al. (2013) supported selective stabilization, and Kim et al. (2011) showed borate+molybdate guidance of formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde mixtures toward pentoses including ribose. The review also notes the limitations of the classical formose route under mild conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Orthophosphate activation of ribose to ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals\", \"borate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"358K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate-rich dry-heating setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"dry-state or low-water activity conditions; cyclic phosphate used as selective glycosyl donor\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ribose is converted into a cyclic phosphate that blocks one face and biases later glycosylation toward beta-N9 products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kim and Benner (2017) identified ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate as a selective precursor enforcing beta and N9 selectivity in adenosine precursor formation. This reaction is included as the activation step implied by that pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Adenine plus ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate to adenosine-2'-phosphate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_024\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals\", \"borate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"358K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"cyclic phosphate-directed glycosylation\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"heating at 85C; exclusive beta-anomer formation reported\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyclic phosphate blocks the alpha-face of ribose and directs selective N9 beta glycosylation of adenine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kim and Benner (2017) showed adenine with ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate at 85C yields adenosine-2'-phosphate in 15% yield with exclusive beta selectivity.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Rearrangement of adenosine-2'-phosphate to adenosine/AMP pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_024\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals\", \"phosphate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"358-363K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"urea-borate assisted phosphate migration context\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"dry-state rearrangement toward biologically relevant phosphorylation position\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The 2'-phosphate intermediate can rearrange under borate/urea-assisted conditions toward the canonical nucleotide pool, furnishing adenosine and especially 5'-phosphorylated AMP as downstream precursors.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kim and Benner (2017) reported that the 2'-phosphate can rearrange toward the biologically relevant 5'-phosphate using urea and borate. This connector is included to link the selective cyclic-phosphate route to the AMP/adenosine network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Ti-mineral-mediated ribosylation of adenine to adenosine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2\", \"borate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"noted as mineral-mediated surface heating conditions\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ti-containing minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"reported N9-ribosylated product selectivity 13:1 over N6 products\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Titanium-containing mineral surfaces template direct ribosylation and favor N9-linked adenosine products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"A 2022 Nature Synthesis study reported Ti-containing minerals catalyze direct ribosylation of adenine with 14% N9-ribosylated products and 13:1 N9:N6 selectivity. This route is included because the review identifies it as the strongest purely mineral-mediated direct purine ribosylation pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Selective phosphorylation of adenosine to AMP\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals\", \"borate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"363K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate-directed phosphate chemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"formamide medium; borate blocks 2' and 3' hydroxyl groups, giving exclusive 5'-AMP\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Borate masks vicinal cis-diols and directs phosphorylation selectively to the 5'-hydroxyl of adenosine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kim et al. (2016) showed adenosine + phosphate + pyrophosphate in formamide at 90C with borate yields exclusively 5'-AMP. This avoids the poorly selective orthophosphate-only route.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"DAP-mediated phosphorylation of adenosine to AMP\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-323K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"diamidophosphate-rich aqueous or paste conditions\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 5.5-10, room temperature to 50C; low-water paste enhances phosphorylation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Activated phosphorus in the form of diamidophosphate phosphorylates nucleosides under mild aqueous to paste conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"DAP phosphorylates nucleosides under prebiotic conditions and later work improved regioselectivity; Gibard et al. (2018) and Cruz et al. (2023). This node is represented using orthophosphate as the network phosphorus pool feeding DAP-like activated chemistry described in the review.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"AMP to ADP phosphorylation in trimetaphosphate wet-dry cycling\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_023\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"wet-dry cycling, historically volcanic settings\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni(II)-assisted trimetaphosphate phosphorylation context\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycles; mixed product distributions reported\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Polyphosphate transfer from cyclic trimetaphosphate extends phosphate chains on adenylates under dehydrating conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Yamagata et al. (1991) and Yamagata/Inomata reported trimetaphosphate with Ni(II) under wet-dry conditions gives substantial adenosine phosphorylation, including ATP among products. Here it is used conservatively as a route from AMP toward ADP prior to the best-supported final ATP step.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"ADP to ATP by acetyl phosphate and Fe3+\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Fe3+\", null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"303K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe3+\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 5.5-6, 2-4 h, water; ~15-20% yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fe3+ forms a macrochelate involving adenine N7, acetyl phosphate, and ADP beta-phosphate, enabling selective phosphoryl transfer to make ATP.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the strongest direct prebiotic ATP synthesis step currently known: acetyl phosphate with Fe3+ converts ADP to ATP in water at 30C and pH 5.5-6 in ~15-20% yield, selectively for ADP; Pinna et al. (2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_020\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct adenosine to ATP phosphorylation by trimetaphosphate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_023\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"wet-dry cycling conditions\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni(II)-catalyzed cTMP chemistry in volcanic polyphosphate settings\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"mixed products including 5'-ATP and cyclic AMP reported\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Polyphosphate transfer from cTMP under dehydrating conditions can directly furnish ATP among a product mixture from adenosine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Yamagata et al. and Inomata achieved total phosphorylation of adenosine with trimetaphosphate under Ni(II)-catalyzed wet-dry cycles, including 13% 5'-ATP. The review emphasizes that this route is less selective than the ADP + acetyl phosphate + Fe3+ pathway.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-to-adenine, cyclic-phosphate nucleoside route, borate AMP, AcP terminal ATP\",\n      \"description\": \"Classical HCN adenine synthesis converges with borate-stabilized ribose and Benner cyclic-phosphate selective purine glycosylation, then proceeds via AMP and ADP to ATP using the strongest terminal step.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide adenine, cyclic-phosphate nucleoside route, borate AMP, AcP terminal ATP\",\n      \"description\": \"Formamide bypasses HCN concentration problems for adenine production, then joins the selective ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate route before the AcP/Fe3+ ATP step.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-to-adenine, Ti-mineral adenosine, borate AMP, AcP terminal ATP\",\n      \"description\": \"Adenine from the Or\u00f3 route is ribosylated by Ti-containing minerals to avoid weak unguided glycosylation, then phosphorylated to ATP via ADP.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide adenine, Ti-mineral adenosine, borate AMP, AcP terminal ATP\",\n      \"description\": \"Formamide-derived adenine converges with borate-guided ribose chemistry and Ti-mineral ribosylation before phosphorylation to ATP.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-to-adenine, Ti-mineral adenosine, DAP-mediated AMP, AcP terminal ATP\",\n      \"description\": \"This branch uses the milder activated-phosphorus DAP phosphorylation rather than borate-formamide phosphorylation before converging on ADP and ATP.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide adenine, Ti-mineral adenosine, DAP-mediated AMP, AcP terminal ATP\",\n      \"description\": \"A formamide-origin purine route combined with Ti-mineral ribosylation and DAP phosphorylation converges on the Pinna ADP-to-ATP step.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde feed, HCN adenine, cyclic-phosphate route, AcP terminal ATP\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal vent chemistry supplies formaldehyde to surface borate sugar chemistry, while adenine comes from HCN oligomerization; the route closes through selective glycosylation and AcP-driven ATP formation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde feed, formamide adenine, Ti-mineral adenosine, AcP terminal ATP\",\n      \"description\": \"This is a strongly multi-environment route: hydrothermal CO2 reduction feeds sugar chemistry, formamide gives adenine, Ti-minerals produce adenosine, and hydrothermal acetyl phosphate powers the final ATP step.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_021\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN adenine with direct cTMP ATP route\",\n      \"description\": \"A shorter but less selective literature-supported branch in which adenosine is directly triphosphorylated by trimetaphosphate under wet-dry conditions.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide adenine with direct cTMP ATP route\",\n      \"description\": \"Formamide supplies adenine, borate-stabilized ribose feeds Ti-mineral adenosine formation, and volcanic trimetaphosphate chemistry gives ATP directly as a mixed phosphorylation product.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_018\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_018\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_019\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "ATP", "overall_strategy": "This network follows the literature-supported multi-environment view that ATP did not arise through a single one-pot pathway. Hydrothermal settings generate reduced C1-C3 feedstocks and a proto-energetic phosphate donor pool; surface settings produce adenine, sugar fragments, ribose-stabilized intermediates, and selective nucleoside/nucleotide assembly under UV, mineral, and wet-dry cycling; biochemical/prebiotic settings complete nucleotide elaboration and the best-supported terminal step, Fe3+-assisted phosphorylation of ADP by acetyl phosphate to ATP. To address known weaknesses, the network avoids treating free-ribose formose chemistry or direct adenine + ribose condensation as the sole central route. Instead it emphasizes literature-supported selective purine nucleoside construction through ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate and Ti-mineral-mediated ribosylation, while retaining ribose stabilization by borate and sugar-fragment chemistry as connected feeder branches. Ten distinct pathways are encoded as different validated route combinations converging on adenosine/AMP/ADP and ending either in the strongest ATP-forming route (acetyl phosphate + Fe3+ from ADP) or the weaker but reported cTMP wet-dry phosphorylation route.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formate/formic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C4H4N4", "iupac_name": "2,3-diaminobut-2-enedinitrile", "common_name": "DAMN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4N4/c5-1-3(7)4(8)2-6/h7-8H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C4H3N5", "iupac_name": "5-amino-1H-imidazole-4-carbonitrile", "common_name": "AICN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H3N5/c5-1-3-2(6)8-4(7)9-3/h(H3,6,7,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H5N5", "iupac_name": "9H-purin-6-amine", "common_name": "adenine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H5N5/c6-5-4-3(8-1-7-4)9-2-10-5/h1-2H,(H2,6,7,8,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "CH2N2", "iupac_name": "cyanamide", "common_name": "cyanamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2N2/c2-1-3/h(H2,2,3)", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H4N2O", "iupac_name": "4,5-dihydro-1,3-oxazol-2-amine", "common_name": "2-aminooxazole", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H8N2O2", "iupac_name": "ribo-aminooxazoline", "common_name": "ribo-aminooxazoline", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H10O5", "iupac_name": "ribose", "common_name": "D/L-ribose", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10O5/c6-1-2(7)3(8)4(9)5(10)11-1/h1-10H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H9O8P", "iupac_name": "ribose 1,2-cyclic phosphate", "common_name": "ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "H3PO4", "iupac_name": "phosphoric acid", "common_name": "orthophosphate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3O4P/c1-5(2,3)4/h(H3,1,2,3,4)", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C10H13N5O4", "iupac_name": "9-beta-D-ribofuranosyl-9H-purin-6-amine", "common_name": "adenosine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C10H13N5O4/c11-10-14-8-6(9(13-10)15-4-12-8)5-1-7(18)19-3(2-16)17-5/h3,5,7,16-18H,1-2H2,(H2,11,12,13,14,15)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C10H14N5O7P", "iupac_name": "[(2R,3R,4S,5R)-5-(6-amino-9H-purin-9-yl)-3,4-dihydroxyoxolan-2-yl]methyl dihydrogen phosphate", "common_name": "AMP", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C10H14N5O7P/c11-10-13-8-6(9(12)14-10)15(4-24-8)1-5(16)7(17)3(2-23-22(18,19)20)21/h3-8,16-17,21H,1-2H2,(H2,18,19,20)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C10H15N5O10P2", "iupac_name": "adenosine 5'-diphosphate", "common_name": "ADP", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C10H15N5O10P2/c11-10-13-8-6(9(12)14-10)15(4-26-8)1-5(16)7(17)3(2-25-27(18,19)24-28(20,21)22)23/h3-8,16-17,23H,1-2H2,(H,18,19)(H2,20,21,22)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "C2H5O5P", "iupac_name": "acetyl dihydrogen phosphate", "common_name": "acetyl phosphate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5O5P/c1-2(3)7-8(4,5)6/h1H3,(H2,4,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "C10H16N5O13P3", "iupac_name": "adenosine 5'-triphosphate", "common_name": "ATP", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C10H16N5O13P3/c11-10-13-8-6(9(12)14-10)15(4-28-8)1-5(16)7(17)3(2-27-31(23,24)29-30(18,19)26-32(20,21)22)25/h3-8,16-17,25H,1-2H2,(H,23,24)(H,18,19)(H2,20,21,22)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_023", "formula": "P3O9(3-)", "iupac_name": "cyclotriphosphate", "common_name": "trimetaphosphate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_024", "formula": "C10H12N5O7P", "iupac_name": "adenosine 2'-phosphate", "common_name": "adenosine-2'-phosphate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite", "mackinawite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "373K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and mackinawite", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-catalyzed hydrogenation of CO2 on iron-sulfur surfaces gives reduced C1 carbon as formate.", "reasoning": "Supported by alkaline hydrothermal vent simulations showing CO2 fixation with H2 on iron-sulfur minerals, including formate production under vent-like alkaline conditions; Herschy et al. (2014) and Preiner et al. (2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal reduction to formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite", "magnetite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "313-363K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Ni-doped mackinawite with magnetite-like hydrothermal surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline vent reactor, proton/pH gradients possible"}, "mechanism": "Partial reduction of CO2 by H2 on sulfide surfaces generates formaldehyde as a reactive carbonyl feedstock.", "reasoning": "Bench-top alkaline vent reactor experiments detected formaldehyde from H2 + CO2 with Ni-doped mackinawite under vent-like conditions; Herschy et al. (2014)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal acetyl phosphate generation from vent proto-metabolism", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_021"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite", "pyrite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "313-363K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "iron-sulfur mineral assemblage", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline hydrothermal setting; connection step is speculative but motivated by acetyl-phosphate-first protoenergetics"}, "mechanism": "Reduced C1 vent carbon chemistry is coupled conceptually to phosphate activation to supply acetyl phosphate as a proto-energetic donor.", "reasoning": "This step is included as a necessary connector rather than a directly demonstrated single-reaction route. The review identifies acetyl phosphate as a plausible proto-ATP in hydrothermal scenarios and notes that integrating its formation geochemically remains unresolved; de Duve (1991, 1995), Lane and Martin as summarized in the review, and Pinna et al. (2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "HCN photoredox synthesis of glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2", "molybdenite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photoredox mineral surface context", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation; literature uses Cu(I)/Cu(II) cyanide photoredox, represented here in a mineral-rich photochemical surface setting"}, "mechanism": "Photoredox homologation of cyanide-derived carbon produces C2 and C3 sugar fragments without requiring free ribose.", "reasoning": "Glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde formation from HCN under UV via copper photoredox was demonstrated by Ritson and Sutherland (2012) and integrated into cyanosulfidic networks by Patel et al. (2015). Mineral agents are included to satisfy network schema for surface settings, but the key literature support is the Cu photoredox chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "HCN oligomerization to DAMN", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2"], "conditions": {"temperature": "278-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "requires concentrated HCN or concentration by freezing/evaporation; alkaline conditions favor oligomerization"}, "mechanism": "Sequential HCN oligomerization furnishes the tetramer diaminomaleonitrile as the key bottleneck intermediate.", "reasoning": "DAMN is the accepted critical intermediate in adenine synthesis from HCN; Sanchez, Ferris and Orgel (1967), Or\u00f3 (1961), Roy et al. (2007), and Sandstr\u00f6m et al. (2025). Mineral surfaces are used here as plausible concentrating substrates, while the core chemistry is literature-supported."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "UV photoisomerization of DAMN to AICN", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-active mineral surface context", "aqueous": true, "other": "strong UV irradiation"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical rearrangement of DAMN furnishes 4-aminoimidazole-5-carbonitrile, a purine-ring precursor.", "reasoning": "Near-quantitative UV photoisomerization of DAMN to AICN is part of the accepted HCN-to-adenine route; Sanchez, Ferris and Orgel (1967), and discussed in the review with Sandstr\u00f6m et al. (2025)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "AICN plus HCN to adenine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "concentrating mineral surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "ammonium cyanide-rich or evaporative settings; days-scale heating possible"}, "mechanism": "Fifth cyanide equivalent closes the purine ring to give adenine.", "reasoning": "This follows the classic Or\u00f3 adenine synthesis framework via HCN pentamerization through DAMN/AICN; Or\u00f3 (1961), Sanchez et al. (1967), Roy et al. (2007), Sandstr\u00f6m et al. (2025)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Formamide mineral-catalyzed adenine synthesis", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "433K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and/or montmorillonite", "aqueous": false, "other": "neat formamide heating"}, "mechanism": "Thermally activated formamide condensation on mineral surfaces yields purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including adenine.", "reasoning": "Heating neat formamide with TiO2 or montmorillonite produces nucleobases, including adenine; Saladino et al. (2003, 2004), with broader iron-sulfur/meteorite extensions in Saladino et al. (2008, 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Cyanamide plus glycolaldehyde to 2-aminooxazole", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "borate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "concentrating evaporitic mineral surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "neutral to mildly basic aqueous conditions"}, "mechanism": "Condensation of glycolaldehyde with cyanamide forms the heterocycle 2-aminooxazole.", "reasoning": "This is the entry step of the Sutherland bypass route to nucleotide chemistry; Anastasi et al. (2006) and Powner et al. (2009)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "2-Aminooxazole plus glyceraldehyde to ribo-aminooxazoline", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate-assisted sugar organization", "aqueous": true, "other": "reported 44% ribo-aminooxazoline with some arabino isomer"}, "mechanism": "C2 and C3 sugar fragments combine through aminooxazole chemistry to give a pentose-derived heterocycle.", "reasoning": "Ribo-aminooxazoline formation from 2-aminooxazole and glyceraldehyde was demonstrated by Anastasi et al. (2006) and underpins the Powner et al. (2009) bypass strategy."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Borate-stabilized pentose formation to ribose", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals", "molybdenite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate and molybdate minerals", "aqueous": true, "other": "alkaline evaporitic pools; borate stabilization and molybdate-guided rearrangements"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde enter borate/molybdate-directed sugar chemistry yielding pentoses including ribose, while borate stabilizes the ribose furanose form.", "reasoning": "Ricardo et al. (2004) showed borate stabilization of ribose, Furukawa et al. (2013) supported selective stabilization, and Kim et al. (2011) showed borate+molybdate guidance of formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde mixtures toward pentoses including ribose. The review also notes the limitations of the classical formose route under mild conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Orthophosphate activation of ribose to ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals", "borate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "358K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate-rich dry-heating setting", "aqueous": false, "other": "dry-state or low-water activity conditions; cyclic phosphate used as selective glycosyl donor"}, "mechanism": "Ribose is converted into a cyclic phosphate that blocks one face and biases later glycosylation toward beta-N9 products.", "reasoning": "Kim and Benner (2017) identified ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate as a selective precursor enforcing beta and N9 selectivity in adenosine precursor formation. This reaction is included as the activation step implied by that pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Adenine plus ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate to adenosine-2'-phosphate", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_024"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals", "borate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "358K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "cyclic phosphate-directed glycosylation", "aqueous": false, "other": "heating at 85C; exclusive beta-anomer formation reported"}, "mechanism": "Cyclic phosphate blocks the alpha-face of ribose and directs selective N9 beta glycosylation of adenine.", "reasoning": "Kim and Benner (2017) showed adenine with ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate at 85C yields adenosine-2'-phosphate in 15% yield with exclusive beta selectivity."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Rearrangement of adenosine-2'-phosphate to adenosine/AMP pool", "inputs": ["mol_024"], "outputs": ["mol_018", "mol_019"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals", "phosphate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "358-363K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "urea-borate assisted phosphate migration context", "aqueous": false, "other": "dry-state rearrangement toward biologically relevant phosphorylation position"}, "mechanism": "The 2'-phosphate intermediate can rearrange under borate/urea-assisted conditions toward the canonical nucleotide pool, furnishing adenosine and especially 5'-phosphorylated AMP as downstream precursors.", "reasoning": "Kim and Benner (2017) reported that the 2'-phosphate can rearrange toward the biologically relevant 5'-phosphate using urea and borate. This connector is included to link the selective cyclic-phosphate route to the AMP/adenosine network."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Ti-mineral-mediated ribosylation of adenine to adenosine", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2", "borate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "noted as mineral-mediated surface heating conditions", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Ti-containing minerals", "aqueous": false, "other": "reported N9-ribosylated product selectivity 13:1 over N6 products"}, "mechanism": "Titanium-containing mineral surfaces template direct ribosylation and favor N9-linked adenosine products.", "reasoning": "A 2022 Nature Synthesis study reported Ti-containing minerals catalyze direct ribosylation of adenine with 14% N9-ribosylated products and 13:1 N9:N6 selectivity. This route is included because the review identifies it as the strongest purely mineral-mediated direct purine ribosylation pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Selective phosphorylation of adenosine to AMP", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals", "borate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "363K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate-directed phosphate chemistry", "aqueous": false, "other": "formamide medium; borate blocks 2' and 3' hydroxyl groups, giving exclusive 5'-AMP"}, "mechanism": "Borate masks vicinal cis-diols and directs phosphorylation selectively to the 5'-hydroxyl of adenosine.", "reasoning": "Kim et al. (2016) showed adenosine + phosphate + pyrophosphate in formamide at 90C with borate yields exclusively 5'-AMP. This avoids the poorly selective orthophosphate-only route."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "DAP-mediated phosphorylation of adenosine to AMP", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-323K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "diamidophosphate-rich aqueous or paste conditions", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 5.5-10, room temperature to 50C; low-water paste enhances phosphorylation"}, "mechanism": "Activated phosphorus in the form of diamidophosphate phosphorylates nucleosides under mild aqueous to paste conditions.", "reasoning": "DAP phosphorylates nucleosides under prebiotic conditions and later work improved regioselectivity; Gibard et al. (2018) and Cruz et al. (2023). This node is represented using orthophosphate as the network phosphorus pool feeding DAP-like activated chemistry described in the review."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "AMP to ADP phosphorylation in trimetaphosphate wet-dry cycling", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_023"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "wet-dry cycling, historically volcanic settings", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Ni(II)-assisted trimetaphosphate phosphorylation context", "aqueous": false, "other": "wet-dry cycles; mixed product distributions reported"}, "mechanism": "Polyphosphate transfer from cyclic trimetaphosphate extends phosphate chains on adenylates under dehydrating conditions.", "reasoning": "Yamagata et al. (1991) and Yamagata/Inomata reported trimetaphosphate with Ni(II) under wet-dry conditions gives substantial adenosine phosphorylation, including ATP among products. Here it is used conservatively as a route from AMP toward ADP prior to the best-supported final ATP step."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "ADP to ATP by acetyl phosphate and Fe3+", "inputs": ["mol_020", "mol_021"], "outputs": ["mol_022"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["Fe3+", null], "conditions": {"temperature": "303K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Fe3+", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 5.5-6, 2-4 h, water; ~15-20% yield"}, "mechanism": "Fe3+ forms a macrochelate involving adenine N7, acetyl phosphate, and ADP beta-phosphate, enabling selective phosphoryl transfer to make ATP.", "reasoning": "This is the strongest direct prebiotic ATP synthesis step currently known: acetyl phosphate with Fe3+ converts ADP to ATP in water at 30C and pH 5.5-6 in ~15-20% yield, selectively for ADP; Pinna et al. (2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_020", "name": "Direct adenosine to ATP phosphorylation by trimetaphosphate", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_023"], "outputs": ["mol_022"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "wet-dry cycling conditions", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Ni(II)-catalyzed cTMP chemistry in volcanic polyphosphate settings", "aqueous": false, "other": "mixed products including 5'-ATP and cyclic AMP reported"}, "mechanism": "Polyphosphate transfer from cTMP under dehydrating conditions can directly furnish ATP among a product mixture from adenosine.", "reasoning": "Yamagata et al. and Inomata achieved total phosphorylation of adenosine with trimetaphosphate under Ni(II)-catalyzed wet-dry cycles, including 13% 5'-ATP. The review emphasizes that this route is less selective than the ADP + acetyl phosphate + Fe3+ pathway."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "HCN-to-adenine, cyclic-phosphate nucleoside route, borate AMP, AcP terminal ATP", "description": "Classical HCN adenine synthesis converges with borate-stabilized ribose and Benner cyclic-phosphate selective purine glycosylation, then proceeds via AMP and ADP to ATP using the strongest terminal step.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_015", "mol_019", "mol_020"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Formamide adenine, cyclic-phosphate nucleoside route, borate AMP, AcP terminal ATP", "description": "Formamide bypasses HCN concentration problems for adenine production, then joins the selective ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate route before the AcP/Fe3+ ATP step.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_008", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_015", "mol_019", "mol_020"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "HCN-to-adenine, Ti-mineral adenosine, borate AMP, AcP terminal ATP", "description": "Adenine from the Or\u00f3 route is ribosylated by Ti-containing minerals to avoid weak unguided glycosylation, then phosphorylated to ATP via ADP.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_011", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_018", "mol_019", "mol_020"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Formamide adenine, Ti-mineral adenosine, borate AMP, AcP terminal ATP", "description": "Formamide-derived adenine converges with borate-guided ribose chemistry and Ti-mineral ribosylation before phosphorylation to ATP.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_008", "rxn_011", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_018", "mol_019", "mol_020"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "HCN-to-adenine, Ti-mineral adenosine, DAP-mediated AMP, AcP terminal ATP", "description": "This branch uses the milder activated-phosphorus DAP phosphorylation rather than borate-formamide phosphorylation before converging on ADP and ATP.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_011", "rxn_015", "rxn_017", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_018", "mol_019", "mol_020"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Formamide adenine, Ti-mineral adenosine, DAP-mediated AMP, AcP terminal ATP", "description": "A formamide-origin purine route combined with Ti-mineral ribosylation and DAP phosphorylation converges on the Pinna ADP-to-ATP step.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_008", "rxn_011", "rxn_015", "rxn_017", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_018", "mol_019", "mol_020"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Hydrothermal formaldehyde feed, HCN adenine, cyclic-phosphate route, AcP terminal ATP", "description": "Hydrothermal vent chemistry supplies formaldehyde to surface borate sugar chemistry, while adenine comes from HCN oligomerization; the route closes through selective glycosylation and AcP-driven ATP formation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_018", "rxn_019"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_011", "mol_015", "mol_020"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Hydrothermal formaldehyde feed, formamide adenine, Ti-mineral adenosine, AcP terminal ATP", "description": "This is a strongly multi-environment route: hydrothermal CO2 reduction feeds sugar chemistry, formamide gives adenine, Ti-minerals produce