rect adenosine-to-ATP route to speculative status\",\n        \"Route through AMP and ADP before ATP\",\n        \"Add Ni(II), wet-dry, and product-distribution caveats if retaining this step\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.93,\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_020\": 0.42\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.68,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.76,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.79,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.7,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.71,\n      \"feedback\": \"Compact but too compressed. The adenine and adenosine steps are plausible, but the direct conversion of adenosine to ATP via cTMP is not nearly as well supported as the ADP plus acetyl phosphate plus Fe3+ route and likely overstates selectivity and yield. This pathway reaches the target but with insufficient confidence.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_020\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Expand through AMP and ADP intermediates\",\n        \"Use the acetyl phosphate/Fe3+ terminal step instead of direct cTMP ATP formation\",\n        \"Treat direct ATP formation from adenosine as minor-product chemistry only\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.86,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"This is a strong, well-connected synthesis network that captures the current literature consensus that ATP prebiotic synthesis is best understood as a multi-environment assembly rather than a single continuous one-pot process. Topologically, the network is dense and connected, with appropriate hubs at adenine, ribose, adenosine, AMP, and ADP, and clear convergence from both HCN and formamide adenine routes as well as multiple nucleotide-assembly options. Environmental interconnection is a major strength: hydrothermal chemistry provides reduced carbon and acetyl phosphate-like energetic intermediates, surface 