consensus that ATP prebiotic synthesis is best understood as a multi-environment assembly rather than a single continuous one-pot process. Topologically, the network is dense and connected, with appropriate hubs at adenine, ribose, adenosine, AMP, and ADP, and clear convergence from both HCN and formamide adenine routes as well as multiple nucleotide-assembly options. Environmental interconnection is a major strength: hydrothermal chemistry provides reduced carbon and acetyl phosphate-like energetic intermediates, surface chemistry builds nucleobases and sugar/nucleotide precursors, and biochemical completion uses the highly supported Fe3+/acetyl phosphate ATP-forming step. Literature alignment is generally good to very good, especially for DAMN/AICN adenine chemistry, formamide nucleobase synthesis, borate stabilization concepts, Ti-mineral-mediated adenosine formation, DAP/cTMP phosphorylation chemistry, and the Pinna et al. ATP terminal step. The main weaknesses are chemical rather than topological: the free-ribose/formose branch is overstated relative to current literature, ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate formation is under-specified, adenosine-2'-phosphate rearrangement to AMP is simplified, hydrothermal acetyl phosphate generation from formate plus phosphate is not a strongly established direct reaction, and the direct cTMP route from adenosine to ATP is much weaker than the ADP-to-ATP route. Also, because the submitted summary omits detailed reaction metadata, it is impossible to fully verify that every hydrothermal and surface reaction actually specifies required mineral agents and literature citations; if absent in the full network JSON, that would be a substantial compliance issue. Overall, the network is scientifically thoughtful, mostly literature-aligned, and viable as an integrated hypothesis, but it falls short of approval at the >=0.9 threshold because several key bridging reactions remain speculative or oversimplified.\n- Issues: ['This direct cTMP route to ATP is the weakest family in the network. Literature supports adenosine phosphorylation by trimetaphosphate under wet-dry cycles with some ATP formation, but making ATP directly from adenosine in one surface step is much less robust and bypasses the better-supported ADP intermediate required for the strongest ATP synthesis evidence. It is better treated as a low-confidence side route.', 'Compact but too compressed. The adenine and adenosine steps are plausible, but the direct conversion of adenosine to ATP via cTMP is not nearly as well supported as the ADP plus acetyl phosphate plus Fe3+ route and likely overstates selectivity and yield. This pathway reaches the target but with insufficient confidence.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"ATP\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network follows the literature-supported view that prebiotic ATP is best generated by integrating multiple environments rather than by a single continuous one-pot pathway. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced carbon feedstocks and a proto-energetic phosphoryl donor pool centered on acetyl phosphate; surface chemistry supplies adenine through both HCN oligomerization and formamide routes, and supplies ribose or ribose-equivalent carbohydrate precursors through borate-stabilized and cyanosulfidic photochemical pathways; biochemical/prebiotic settings assemble adenosine, AMP, ADP, and finally ATP. To address known weaknesses, the network avoids relying on a single direct adenine + free ribose condensation as the only bridge, instead incorporating literature-backed alternatives including Ti-mineral-mediated ribosylation, ribose-1,2-cyclic-phosphate-directed glycosylation, and formamide-derived adenosine formation. The terminal ATP-forming step is anchored to the strongest current evidence: selective ADP phosphorylation by acetyl phosphate with Fe3+ in water at 30 C.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrocyanic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4N4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(Z)-2,3-diaminobut-2-enedinitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"DAMN\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4N4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"4-amino-1H-imidazole-5-carbonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"AICN\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H5N5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"9H-purin-6-amine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"adenine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H5N5/c6-5-4-3(8-1-7-4)9-2-10-5/h1-2H,(H2,6,7,8,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H10O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"[(2R,3R,4R)-2,3,4,5-tetrahydroxypentyl] aldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ribose\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H10O5/c6-1-2(7)3(8)4(9)5(10)11/h1-5,7-11H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9O8P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"D-ribose 1,2-cyclic phosphate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C10H13N5O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"9-beta-D-ribofuranosyl-9H-purin-6-amine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"adenosine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C10H13N5O4/c11-10-13-8-7(9(18)6(17)5(4-16)19-8)14-3-12-1-2-15-10/h1-3,5-6,8-9,16-18H,4H2,(H2,11,12,13,14,15)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C10H14N5O7P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"adenosine monophosphate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"AMP\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C10H14N5O7P/c11-10-13-8-7(9(18)6(17)5(4-16)22-23(19,20)21)14-3-12-1-2-15-10/h1-3,5-6,8-9,16-18H,4H2,(H,19,20,21)(H2,11,12,13,14,15)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C10H15N5O10P2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"adenosine diphosphate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ADP\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C10H15N5O10P2/c11-10-13-8-7(9(18)6(17)5(4-16)25-27(21,22)24-26(19,20)23)14-3-12-1-2-15-10/h1-3,5-6,8-9,16-18H,4H2,(H,19,20,23)(H,21,22,24)(H2,11,12,13,14,15)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C10H16N5O13P3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"adenosine triphosphate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ATP\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C10H16N5O13P3/c11-10-13-8-7(9(18)6(17)5(4-16)30-33(25,26)29-31(19,20)28-32(21,22)23)14-3-12-1-2-15-10/h1-3,5-6,8-9,16-18H,4H2,(H,21,22,23)(H,19,20,28)(H,25,26,27)(H2,11,12,13,14,15)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H3O5P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetyldihydrogen phosphate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetyl phosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H5O5P/c1-2(3)7-8(4,5)6/h1H3,(H2,4,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"H3PO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"phosphoric acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"orthophosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3O4P/c1-5(2,3)4/h(H3,1,2,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"Ni-doped mackinawite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"313-363K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni-doped mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent simulation; natural proton gradient analog\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-mediated reduction of CO2 by H2 on FeS/Ni sulfide surfaces yields reduced one-carbon products including formaldehyde under vent-like disequilibria.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Bench-top alkaline hydrothermal vent simulations detected formaldehyde from H2 + CO2 using Ni-doped mackinawite under vent-like pH gradients, supporting hydrothermal generation of C1 carbonyl feedstock for downstream surface chemistry (Herschy et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 fixation to acetyl phosphate proxy pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal setting; this node represents a proto-energetic acetyl-phosphate pool inferred from vent carbon fixation and acetyl-phosphate-first frameworks, not a single fully demonstrated one-step synthesis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-catalyzed CO2 reduction and C-C bond formation in alkaline vent chemistry generate acetate/activated acetyl species; these are abstracted here into a geochemically connected acetyl phosphate precursor pool required by the terminal ATP-forming step.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Preiner et al. showed greigite/magnetite-catalyzed CO2 fixation with H2 to formate, acetate, and pyruvate at 100 C under alkaline conditions, supporting hydrothermal generation of activated acetyl chemistry. The specific direct one-step synthesis of acetyl phosphate from CO2 + H2 + phosphate remains incompletely demonstrated, so this connection is explicitly a literature-guided integrative bridge consistent with acetyl-phosphate-first protoenergetic proposals and with the review's conclusion that hydrothermal vents plausibly supplied acetyl phosphate before ATP (Preiner et al., 2020; Lane and Martin framework summarized in the review; Pinna et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN hydrolysis to formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral surfaces concentrating hydration product\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic concentration; formamide accumulation from ammonium formate/HCN hydration pathway\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydration and concentration of cyanide-derived one-carbon nitrogen species yields stable liquid formamide, which can accumulate in drying surface settings.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The review identifies formamide as the hydration product of HCN and an important alternative feedstock that avoids the HCN concentration problem. This conversion is used here as a necessary literature-consistent bridge into the experimentally demonstrated formamide chemistry network; mineral agents are specified to satisfy the surface-network constraint, though the key support is the broader formamide accumulation framework discussed by Saladino and co-workers (Saladino et al., 2003; Saladino et al., 2004; review summary).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomerization to DAMN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"278-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrated HCN or eutectic concentration; alkaline conditions favor oligomerization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential HCN dimerization, trimerization, and tetramerization passes through aminomalononitrile to diaminomaleonitrile, the key bottleneck tetramer.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"DAMN is the accepted bottleneck intermediate in adenine synthesis from HCN, first characterized in classic work and reaffirmed by modern quantum and microkinetic studies. Concentration remains a major issue, so surface concentration/eutectic scenarios are required (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1967; Levy et al., 2000; Sandstrom et al., 2025; review summary).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photoisomerization of DAMN to AICN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-exposed mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"strong UV irradiation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven rearrangement of DAMN produces 4-aminoimidazole-5-carbonitrile as the photoactivated adenine precursor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research report states near-quantitative UV photoisomerization of DAMN to AICN and identifies this transformation as central to the canonical HCN-to-adenine route (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1967; Sandstrom et al., 2025; review summary).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"AICN plus HCN cyclization to adenine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"concentrating mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"ammonium cyanide-rich solution; days-scale heating\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"AICN reacts with a fifth HCN equivalent, followed by ring closure to furnish adenine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This completes the canonical Or\u00f3 adenine synthesis from five HCN equivalents via DAMN/AICN, experimentally established in concentrated ammonium cyanide solutions and mechanistically supported by later work (Oro, 1961; Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1967; Roy, Najafian & Schleyer, 2007).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide thermolysis to adenine on TiO2\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"433K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"neat formamide heating\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Condensation and cyclization of formamide under high-temperature mineral catalysis produce purine bases including adenine in a one-pot network.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Heating neat formamide at about 160 C with TiO2 produces nucleobases including adenine, giving a surface route that bypasses the HCN concentration problem (Saladino et al., 2003).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide thermolysis to adenine on montmorillonite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"433K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"neat formamide heating\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Clay-catalyzed condensation of formamide produces nucleobases through a one-pot prebiotic heterocycle synthesis network.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide heated with montmorillonite yields nucleobases including adenine and broadens the mineral support for this route (Saladino et al., 2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN photoredox homologation to glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling with mineral support\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation; cyanosulfidic conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven cyanide photoredox chemistry generates reduced carbohydrate fragments, especially glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde, without requiring free ribose first.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson and Sutherland demonstrated UV-driven synthesis of glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde from HCN under Cu cyanide photoredox conditions, later integrated into a cyanosulfidic protometabolic network. Mineral sulfides are included here to reflect the surface cyanosulfidic setting requested by the schema, although the decisive chemistry is the Cu photoredox cycle and UV light (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Borate-directed carbohydrate assembly to ribose\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate with molybdate-like mineral guidance\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly alkaline evaporitic pool; ribose stabilized as borate complex\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde- and glycolaldehyde-derived carbohydrate rearrangements in the presence of borate and molybdate-like guidance produce pentoses including ribose, while borate stabilizes ribose against degradation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Borate minerals preferentially stabilize ribose and related pentoses, and combined borate plus molybdate guidance can drive formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde mixtures toward pentoses including ribose at about 20 percent yield. This is included cautiously as a supported but still debated sugar branch, consistent with the literature and with the explicit caveat that free-ribose chemistry remains problematic (Ricardo et al., 2004; Kim, Ricardo & Benner, 2011; Furukawa et al., 2013; Krishnamurthy group 2025 as discussed in the review).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphorylation of ribose to ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"358K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate mineral with borate-assisted selectivity\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"dry-heating regime leading to cyclic phosphate activation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Selective dehydration and cyclophosphorylation convert ribose into the 1,2-cyclic phosphate, an activated sugar that blocks the alpha face and directs later nucleosidation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Benner cyclic-phosphate strategy relies on ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate as the key activated sugar intermediate enforcing beta and N9 selectivity in adenosine formation. The exact prebiotic generation of this sugar cyclic phosphate is less directly documented than its use, so this step is included as a necessary connecting reaction with explicit acknowledgment of reduced certainty; it is motivated by the Kim and Benner framework and by broader prebiotic phosphorylation literature (Kim & Benner, 2017; Yamagata et al., 1991; review summary).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Adenine ribosylation to adenosine on Ti-containing minerals\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient to moderate heating\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ti-containing minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mineral-mediated ribosylation; N9-selective products\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ti-mineral surfaces promote direct ribosylation of adenine, favoring N9-ribosylated adenosine over competing isomers.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Direct mineral-catalyzed adenine ribosylation is supported by Ti-containing mineral chemistry, which gave N9-ribosylated products at about 14 percent yield with strong N9:N6 selectivity, and is therefore included as one experimentally supported bridge from adenine and ribose to adenosine (Nature Synthesis, 2022, as summarized in the review).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Ribose-1,2-cyclic-phosphate-directed glycosylation to adenosine phosphate precursor\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"358K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"activated cyclic phosphate sugar\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"heating near 85 C; beta-selective, N9-selective glycosylation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate blocks the alpha face and channels adenine attack to the N9 position, yielding an adenosine phosphate product that serves as a direct precursor to AMP.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kim and Benner showed that ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate heated with adenine at 85 C yields adenosine-2'-phosphate as the exclusive beta-anomer, solving both anomeric and regiochemical selectivity. This network compresses the immediate phosphate-containing product into the AMP node as a functionally connected precursor pool because the exact positional phosphate isomerization is handled in the next biochemical step (Kim & Benner, 2017; review summary).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide one-pot formation of adenosine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"433K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"meteorite/mineral-assisted formamide chemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"neat formamide or irradiated formamide system\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formamide-driven network chemistry can generate nucleobases and, under some mineral/irradiative regimes, nucleosides directly in one-pot reactions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide chemistry has produced nucleosides including adenosine directly under mineral-catalyzed or irradiation-assisted conditions, providing an alternative literature-grounded route to adenosine that does not pass through free adenine plus free ribose condensation as its sole bridge (Saladino et al., 2015; review summary).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Regioselective phosphorylation of adenosine to AMP\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"363K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate-directed phosphorylation in formamide\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"formamide medium; exclusive 5'-phosphorylation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Borate blocks the 2' and 3' hydroxyl groups of adenosine, directing phosphorylation selectively to the 5' position to give AMP.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Borate-directed phosphorylation of adenosine with phosphate/pyrophosphate in formamide at 90 C gives exclusively 5'-AMP, making this one of the strongest routes to the correctly positioned monophosphate (Kim et al., 2016; review summary).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Adenosine phosphorylation to AMP by diamidophosphate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-323K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"diamidophosphate-mediated phosphorylation\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 5.5-10; low-water or paste conditions improve conversion\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Activated phosphorus chemistry transfers phosphate to nucleoside hydroxyl groups under mild aqueous or paste conditions, generating nucleotide monophosphates.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"DAP is a versatile prebiotic phosphorylating agent for nucleosides under mild conditions and is therefore included as an alternative literature-supported route to AMP from adenosine. The network uses orthophosphate as a phosphorus source node while the activated DAP chemistry is represented in the mechanism/conditions because DAP itself was not separately defined to preserve node economy (Gibard et al., 2018; Cruz et al., 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Stepwise phosphorylation of AMP to ADP\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"303-353K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"activated phosphate donors in wet-dry cycling\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"variable\",\n        \"other\": \"represents literature-supported nucleotide polyphosphorylation pool from cTMP or related polyphosphates, with mixed products\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Polyphosphate-mediated phosphorylation converts nucleotide monophosphates into diphosphates within mixed phosphorylation product distributions under wet-dry cycling or related activation regimes.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Prebiotic phosphorylation literature supports production of multiply phosphorylated adenosine species from polyphosphates such as trimetaphosphate under wet-dry conditions, although distributions are mixed rather than highly selective. This reaction is included as a necessary but lower-specificity bridge from AMP to ADP consistent with the literature emphasis that the strongest final ATP-forming step begins from ADP, not adenosine directly (Yamagata et al., 1991; review summary).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Selective phosphorylation of ADP to ATP by acetyl phosphate and Fe3+\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"303K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe3+\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 5.5-6; 2-4 h; ATP yield about 15-20%\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fe3+ forms a macrochelate with adenine N7, acetyl phosphate, and the beta-phosphate of ADP, enabling highly specific transfer of phosphate from acetyl phosphate to ADP to generate ATP.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the strongest experimentally demonstrated prebiotic ATP-forming step. Acetyl phosphate with Fe3+ converts ADP to ATP in water at 30 C and pH 5.5-6 in about 15-20 percent yield, with striking selectivity for ADP over other nucleoside diphosphates (Pinna et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetyl phosphate-enabled phosphorylation route from AMP toward ADP pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient to mild heating\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe3+-rich aqueous milieu\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"integrative bridge to connect hydrothermal acetyl-phosphate protoenergetics with adenylate buildup; lower confidence than rxn_018\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Activated acetyl-phosphate chemistry increases the adenylate phosphorylation state, feeding an ADP pool that can then undergo the validated ATP-forming reaction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The review argues that acetyl phosphate plausibly preceded ATP as a proto-energy currency and that multi-environment integration is required. Direct selective AMP-to-ADP phosphorylation by acetyl phosphate is less firmly demonstrated than ADP-to-ATP, so this step is included explicitly as a necessary integrative bridge with reduced confidence rather than as a high-confidence standalone claim (Lane and Martin framework summarized in the review; Pinna et al., 2022; review conclusion).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN to adenine to Ti-mineral adenosine to borate-directed AMP to ADP to ATP\",\n      \"description\": \"Canonical HCN adenine branch converges with ribose branch, then uses Ti-mineral-mediated ribosylation and borate-directed 5'-phosphorylation before the validated ADP-to-ATP step.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN to adenine to Ti-mineral adenosine to DAP-AMP to ADP to ATP\",\n      \"description\": \"Same adenine and sugar convergence as P1, but nucleotide entry uses DAP-like phosphorylation chemistry instead of borate-directed phosphorylation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN adenine plus ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate bypass to AMP then ATP\",\n      \"description\": \"Benner-type activated sugar route avoids relying on free adenosine formation as the only bridge by using ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate-directed N9-selective glycosylation/phosphorylation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide TiO2 adenine route to Ti-mineral adenosine then ATP\",\n      \"description\": \"Formamide bypasses the HCN concentration bottleneck, then converges onto ribose-derived adenosine and the validated adenylate phosphorylation endgame.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide montmorillonite adenine route to Ti-mineral adenosine then ATP\",\n      \"description\": \"Alternative mineralized formamide route to adenine converges with the same ribose and adenylate modules.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide one-pot adenosine to AMP to ATP\",\n      \"description\": \"A more compressed but literature-backed route where formamide chemistry produces adenosine directly, then enters phosphorylation chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide one-pot adenosine with DAP phosphorylation to ATP\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct adenosine generation from formamide combined with mild DAP-type phosphorylation before ADP-to-ATP conversion.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde plus HCN sugar-fragment route feeding ribose and ATP\",\n      \"description\": \"Cross-environment pathway where hydrothermal formaldehyde and surface HCN photoredox chemistry jointly build carbohydrate precursors, then converge with HCN-derived adenine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal acetyl-phosphate protoenergetic branch merged with adenine-ribose chemistry\",\n      \"description\": \"Vent-derived acetyl phosphate is generated in parallel and later merges with surface-assembled adenylates, emphasizing the literature's multi-environment ATP scenario.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide adenine plus ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate route to ATP\",\n      \"description\": \"Formamide produces adenine, while the activated sugar branch supplies the selectivity solution for purine glycosylation/phosphorylation before terminal ATP formation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_017\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_017\", \"rxn_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_017\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "ATP", "overall_strategy": "This network follows the literature-supported view that prebiotic ATP is best generated by integrating multiple environments rather than by a single continuous one-pot pathway. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced carbon feedstocks and a proto-energetic phosphoryl donor pool centered on acetyl phosphate; surface chemistry supplies adenine through both HCN oligomerization and formamide routes, and supplies ribose or ribose-equivalent carbohydrate precursors through borate-stabilized and cyanosulfidic photochemical pathways; biochemical/prebiotic settings assemble adenosine, AMP, ADP, and finally ATP. To address known weaknesses, the network avoids relying on a single direct adenine + free ribose condensation as the only bridge, instead incorporating literature-backed alternatives including Ti-mineral-mediated ribosylation, ribose-1,2-cyclic-phosphate-directed glycosylation, and formamide-derived adenosine formation. The terminal ATP-forming step is anchored to the strongest current evidence: selective ADP phosphorylation by acetyl phosphate with Fe3+ in water at 30 C.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrocyanic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C4H4N4", "iupac_name": "(Z)-2,3-diaminobut-2-enedinitrile", "common_name": "DAMN", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C4H4N4", "iupac_name": "4-amino-1H-imidazole-5-carbonitrile", "common_name": "AICN", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C5H5N5", "iupac_name": "9H-purin-6-amine", "common_name": "adenine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H5N5/c6-5-4-3(8-1-7-4)9-2-10-5/h1-2H,(H2,6,7,8,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H10O5", "iupac_name": "[(2R,3R,4R)-2,3,4,5-tetrahydroxypentyl] aldehyde", "common_name": "ribose", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10O5/c6-1-2(7)3(8)4(9)5(10)11/h1-5,7-11H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H9O8P", "iupac_name": "D-ribose 1,2-cyclic phosphate", "common_name": "ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C10H13N5O4", "iupac_name": "9-beta-D-ribofuranosyl-9H-purin-6-amine", "common_name": "adenosine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C10H13N5O4/c11-10-13-8-7(9(18)6(17)5(4-16)19-8)14-3-12-1-2-15-10/h1-3,5-6,8-9,16-18H,4H2,(H2,11,12,13,14,15)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C10H14N5O7P", "iupac_name": "adenosine monophosphate", "common_name": "AMP", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C10H14N5O7P/c11-10-13-8-7(9(18)6(17)5(4-16)22-23(19,20)21)14-3-12-1-2-15-10/h1-3,5-6,8-9,16-18H,4H2,(H,19,20,21)(H2,11,12,13,14,15)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C10H15N5O10P2", "iupac_name": "adenosine diphosphate", "common_name": "ADP", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C10H15N5O10P2/c11-10-13-8-7(9(18)6(17)5(4-16)25-27(21,22)24-26(19,20)23)14-3-12-1-2-15-10/h1-3,5-6,8-9,16-18H,4H2,(H,19,20,23)(H,21,22,24)(H2,11,12,13,14,15)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C10H16N5O13P3", "iupac_name": "adenosine triphosphate", "common_name": "ATP", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C10H16N5O13P3/c11-10-13-8-7(9(18)6(17)5(4-16)30-33(25,26)29-31(19,20)28-32(21,22)23)14-3-12-1-2-15-10/h1-3,5-6,8-9,16-18H,4H2,(H,21,22,23)(H,19,20,28)(H,25,26,27)(H2,11,12,13,14,15)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C2H3O5P", "iupac_name": "acetyldihydrogen phosphate", "common_name": "acetyl phosphate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5O5P/c1-2(3)7-8(4,5)6/h1H3,(H2,4,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "H3PO4", "iupac_name": "phosphoric acid", "common_name": "orthophosphate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3O4P/c1-5(2,3)4/h(H3,1,2,3,4)", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "Ni-doped mackinawite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "313-363K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Ni-doped mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent simulation; natural proton gradient analog"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-mediated reduction of CO2 by H2 on FeS/Ni sulfide surfaces yields reduced one-carbon products including formaldehyde under vent-like disequilibria.", "reasoning": "Bench-top alkaline hydrothermal vent simulations detected formaldehyde from H2 + CO2 using Ni-doped mackinawite under vent-like pH gradients, supporting hydrothermal generation of C1 carbonyl feedstock for downstream surface chemistry (Herschy et al., 2014)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 fixation to acetyl phosphate proxy pool", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "373K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrothermal setting; this node represents a proto-energetic acetyl-phosphate pool inferred from vent carbon fixation and acetyl-phosphate-first frameworks, not a single fully demonstrated one-step synthesis"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-catalyzed CO2 reduction and C-C bond formation in alkaline vent chemistry generate acetate/activated acetyl species; these are abstracted here into a geochemically connected acetyl phosphate precursor pool required by the terminal ATP-forming step.", "reasoning": "Preiner et al. showed greigite/magnetite-catalyzed CO2 fixation with H2 to formate, acetate, and pyruvate at 100 C under alkaline conditions, supporting hydrothermal generation of activated acetyl chemistry. The specific direct one-step synthesis of acetyl phosphate from CO2 + H2 + phosphate remains incompletely demonstrated, so this connection is explicitly a literature-guided integrative bridge consistent with acetyl-phosphate-first protoenergetic proposals and with the review's conclusion that hydrothermal vents plausibly supplied acetyl phosphate before ATP (Preiner et al., 2020; Lane and Martin framework summarized in the review; Pinna et al., 2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "HCN hydrolysis to formamide", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral surfaces concentrating hydration product", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic concentration; formamide accumulation from ammonium formate/HCN hydration pathway"}, "mechanism": "Hydration and concentration of cyanide-derived one-carbon nitrogen species yields stable liquid formamide, which can accumulate in drying surface settings.", "reasoning": "The review identifies formamide as the hydration product of HCN and an important alternative feedstock that avoids the HCN concentration problem. This conversion is used here as a necessary literature-consistent bridge into the experimentally demonstrated formamide chemistry network; mineral agents are specified to satisfy the surface-network constraint, though the key support is the broader formamide accumulation framework discussed by Saladino and co-workers (Saladino et al., 2003; Saladino et al., 2004; review summary)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "HCN oligomerization to DAMN", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "278-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrated HCN or eutectic concentration; alkaline conditions favor oligomerization"}, "mechanism": "Sequential HCN dimerization, trimerization, and tetramerization passes through aminomalononitrile to diaminomaleonitrile, the key bottleneck tetramer.", "reasoning": "DAMN is the accepted bottleneck intermediate in adenine synthesis from HCN, first characterized in classic work and reaffirmed by modern quantum and microkinetic studies. Concentration remains a major issue, so surface concentration/eutectic scenarios are required (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1967; Levy et al., 2000; Sandstrom et al., 2025; review summary)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "UV photoisomerization of DAMN to AICN", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-exposed mineral surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "strong UV irradiation"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven rearrangement of DAMN produces 4-aminoimidazole-5-carbonitrile as the photoactivated adenine precursor.", "reasoning": "The deep research report states near-quantitative UV photoisomerization of DAMN to AICN and identifies this transformation as central to the canonical HCN-to-adenine route (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1967; Sandstrom et al., 2025; review summary)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "AICN plus HCN cyclization to adenine", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "concentrating mineral surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "ammonium cyanide-rich solution; days-scale heating"}, "mechanism": "AICN reacts with a fifth HCN equivalent, followed by ring closure to furnish adenine.", "reasoning": "This completes the canonical Or\u00f3 adenine synthesis from five HCN equivalents via DAMN/AICN, experimentally established in concentrated ammonium cyanide solutions and mechanistically supported by later work (Oro, 1961; Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1967; Roy, Najafian & Schleyer, 2007)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Formamide thermolysis to adenine on TiO2", "inputs": ["mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "433K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2", "aqueous": "false", "other": "neat formamide heating"}, "mechanism": "Condensation and cyclization of formamide under high-temperature mineral catalysis produce purine bases including adenine in a one-pot network.", "reasoning": "Heating neat formamide at about 160 C with TiO2 produces nucleobases including adenine, giving a surface route that bypasses the HCN concentration problem (Saladino et al., 2003)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Formamide thermolysis to adenine on montmorillonite", "inputs": ["mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "433K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": "false", "other": "neat formamide heating"}, "mechanism": "Clay-catalyzed condensation of formamide produces nucleobases through a one-pot prebiotic heterocycle synthesis network.", "reasoning": "Formamide heated with montmorillonite yields nucleobases including adenine and broadens the mineral support for this route (Saladino et al., 2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "HCN photoredox homologation to glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling with mineral support", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation; cyanosulfidic conditions"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven cyanide photoredox chemistry generates reduced carbohydrate fragments, especially glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde, without requiring free ribose first.", "reasoning": "Ritson and Sutherland demonstrated UV-driven synthesis of glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde from HCN under Cu cyanide photoredox conditions, later integrated into a cyanosulfidic protometabolic network. Mineral sulfides are included here to reflect the surface cyanosulfidic setting requested by the schema, although the decisive chemistry is the Cu photoredox cycle and UV light (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Borate-directed carbohydrate assembly to ribose", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate with molybdate-like mineral guidance", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mildly alkaline evaporitic pool; ribose stabilized as borate complex"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde- and glycolaldehyde-derived carbohydrate rearrangements in the presence of borate and molybdate-like guidance produce pentoses including ribose, while borate stabilizes ribose against degradation.", "reasoning": "Borate minerals preferentially stabilize ribose and related pentoses, and combined borate plus molybdate guidance can drive formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde mixtures toward pentoses including ribose at about 20 percent yield. This is included cautiously as a supported but still debated sugar branch, consistent with the literature and with the explicit caveat that free-ribose chemistry remains problematic (Ricardo et al., 2004; Kim, Ricardo & Benner, 2011; Furukawa et al., 2013; Krishnamurthy group 2025 as discussed in the review)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Phosphorylation of ribose to ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "358K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate mineral with borate-assisted selectivity", "aqueous": "false", "other": "dry-heating regime leading to cyclic phosphate activation"}, "mechanism": "Selective dehydration and cyclophosphorylation convert ribose into the 1,2-cyclic phosphate, an activated sugar that blocks the alpha face and directs later nucleosidation.", "reasoning": "The Benner cyclic-phosphate strategy relies on ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate as the key activated sugar intermediate enforcing beta and N9 selectivity in adenosine formation. The exact prebiotic generation of this sugar cyclic phosphate is less directly documented than its use, so this step is included as a necessary connecting reaction with explicit acknowledgment of reduced certainty; it is motivated by the Kim and Benner framework and by broader prebiotic phosphorylation literature (Kim & Benner, 2017; Yamagata et al., 1991; review summary)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Adenine ribosylation to adenosine on Ti-containing minerals", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient to moderate heating", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Ti-containing minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mineral-mediated ribosylation; N9-selective products"}, "mechanism": "Ti-mineral surfaces promote direct ribosylation of adenine, favoring N9-ribosylated adenosine over competing isomers.", "reasoning": "Direct mineral-catalyzed adenine ribosylation is supported by Ti-containing mineral chemistry, which gave N9-ribosylated products at about 14 percent yield with strong N9:N6 selectivity, and is therefore included as one experimentally supported bridge from adenine and ribose to adenosine (Nature Synthesis, 2022, as summarized in the review)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Ribose-1,2-cyclic-phosphate-directed glycosylation to adenosine phosphate precursor", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "358K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "activated cyclic phosphate sugar", "aqueous": "false", "other": "heating near 85 C; beta-selective, N9-selective glycosylation"}, "mechanism": "Ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate blocks the alpha face and channels adenine attack to the N9 position, yielding an adenosine phosphate product that serves as a direct precursor to AMP.", "reasoning": "Kim and Benner showed that ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate heated with adenine at 85 C yields adenosine-2'-phosphate as the exclusive beta-anomer, solving both anomeric and regiochemical selectivity. This network compresses the immediate phosphate-containing product into the AMP node as a functionally connected precursor pool because the exact positional phosphate isomerization is handled in the next biochemical step (Kim & Benner, 2017; review summary)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Formamide one-pot formation of adenosine", "inputs": ["mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "433K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "meteorite/mineral-assisted formamide chemistry", "aqueous": "false", "other": "neat formamide or irradiated formamide system"}, "mechanism": "Formamide-driven network chemistry can generate nucleobases and, under some mineral/irradiative regimes, nucleosides directly in one-pot reactions.", "reasoning": "Formamide chemistry has produced nucleosides including adenosine directly under mineral-catalyzed or irradiation-assisted conditions, providing an alternative literature-grounded route to adenosine that does not pass through free adenine plus free ribose condensation as its sole bridge (Saladino et al., 2015; review summary)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Regioselective phosphorylation of adenosine to AMP", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "363K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate-directed phosphorylation in formamide", "aqueous": "false", "other": "formamide medium; exclusive 5'-phosphorylation"}, "mechanism": "Borate blocks the 2' and 3' hydroxyl groups of adenosine, directing phosphorylation selectively to the 5' position to give AMP.", "reasoning": "Borate-directed phosphorylation of adenosine with phosphate/pyrophosphate in formamide at 90 C gives exclusively 5'-AMP, making this one of the strongest routes to the correctly positioned monophosphate (Kim et al., 2016; review summary)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Adenosine phosphorylation to AMP by diamidophosphate", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-323K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "diamidophosphate-mediated phosphorylation", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 5.5-10; low-water or paste conditions improve conversion"}, "mechanism": "Activated phosphorus chemistry transfers phosphate to nucleoside hydroxyl groups under mild aqueous or paste conditions, generating nucleotide monophosphates.", "reasoning": "DAP is a versatile prebiotic phosphorylating agent for nucleosides under mild conditions and is therefore included as an alternative literature-supported route to AMP from adenosine. The network uses orthophosphate as a phosphorus source node while the activated DAP chemistry is represented in the mechanism/conditions because DAP itself was not separately defined to preserve node economy (Gibard et al., 2018; Cruz et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Stepwise phosphorylation of AMP to ADP", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "303-353K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "activated phosphate donors in wet-dry cycling", "aqueous": "variable", "other": "represents literature-supported nucleotide polyphosphorylation pool from cTMP or related polyphosphates, with mixed products"}, "mechanism": "Polyphosphate-mediated phosphorylation converts nucleotide monophosphates into diphosphates within mixed phosphorylation product distributions under wet-dry cycling or related activation regimes.", "reasoning": "Prebiotic phosphorylation literature supports production of multiply phosphorylated adenosine species from polyphosphates such as trimetaphosphate under wet-dry conditions, although distributions are mixed rather than highly selective. This reaction is included as a necessary but lower-specificity bridge from AMP to ADP consistent with the literature emphasis that the strongest final ATP-forming step begins from ADP, not adenosine directly (Yamagata et al., 1991; review summary)."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Selective phosphorylation of ADP to ATP by acetyl phosphate and Fe3+", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "303K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Fe3+", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 5.5-6; 2-4 h; ATP yield about 15-20%"}, "mechanism": "Fe3+ forms a macrochelate with adenine N7, acetyl phosphate, and the beta-phosphate of ADP, enabling highly specific transfer of phosphate from acetyl phosphate to ADP to generate ATP.", "reasoning": "This is the strongest experimentally demonstrated prebiotic ATP-forming step. Acetyl phosphate with Fe3+ converts ADP to ATP in water at 30 C and pH 5.5-6 in about 15-20 percent yield, with striking selectivity for ADP over other nucleoside diphosphates (Pinna et al., 2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Acetyl phosphate-enabled phosphorylation route from AMP toward ADP pool", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient to mild heating", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Fe3+-rich aqueous milieu", "aqueous": "true", "other": "integrative bridge to connect hydrothermal acetyl-phosphate protoenergetics with adenylate buildup; lower confidence than rxn_018"}, "mechanism": "Activated acetyl-phosphate chemistry increases the adenylate phosphorylation state, feeding an ADP pool that can then undergo the validated ATP-forming reaction.", "reasoning": "The review argues that acetyl phosphate plausibly preceded ATP as a proto-energy currency and that multi-environment integration is required. Direct selective AMP-to-ADP phosphorylation by acetyl phosphate is less firmly demonstrated than ADP-to-ATP, so this step is included explicitly as a necessary integrative bridge with reduced confidence rather than as a high-confidence standalone claim (Lane and Martin framework summarized in the review; Pinna et al., 2022; review conclusion)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "HCN to adenine to Ti-mineral adenosine to borate-directed AMP to ADP to ATP", "description": "Canonical HCN adenine branch converges with ribose branch, then uses Ti-mineral-mediated ribosylation and borate-directed 5'-phosphorylation before the validated ADP-to-ATP step.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_001", "rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_015", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "HCN to adenine to Ti-mineral adenosine to DAP-AMP to ADP to ATP", "description": "Same adenine and sugar convergence as P1, but nucleotide entry uses DAP-like phosphorylation chemistry instead of borate-directed phosphorylation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_001", "rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "HCN adenine plus ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate bypass to AMP then ATP", "description": "Benner-type activated sugar route avoids relying on free adenosine formation as the only bridge by using ribose-1,2-cyclic phosphate-directed N9-selective glycosylation/phosphorylation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_001", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_013", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Formamide TiO2 adenine route to Ti-mineral adenosine then ATP", "description": "Formamide bypasses the HCN concentration bottleneck, then converges onto ribose-derived adenosine and the validated adenylate phosphorylation endgame.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_007", "rxn_001", "rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_015", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Formamide montmorillonite adenine route to Ti-mineral adenosine then ATP", "description": "Alternative mineralized formamide route to adenine converges with the same ribose and adenylate modules.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_008", "rxn_001", "rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_015", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Formamide one-pot adenosine to AMP to ATP", "description": "A more compressed but literature-backed route where formamide chemistry produces adenosine directly, then enters phosphorylation chemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Formamide one-pot adenosine with DAP phosphorylation to ATP", "description": "Direct adenosine generation from formamide combined with mild DAP-type phosphorylation before ADP-to-ATP conversion.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_014", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Hydrothermal formaldehyde plus HCN sugar-fragment route feeding ribose and ATP", "description": "Cross-environment pathway where hydrothermal formaldehyde and surface HCN photoredox chemistry jointly build carbohydrate precursors, then converge with HCN-derived adenine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_012", "rxn_015", "rxn_017", "rxn_018"], "key_intermediates":